{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"language":"python","display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3.12.12","mimetype":"text/x-python","codemirror_mode":{"name":"ipython","version":3},"pygments_lexer":"ipython3","nbconvert_exporter":"python","file_extension":".py"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[{"sourceType":"kernelVersion","sourceId":303774003}],"dockerImageVersionId":31328,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"python","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"# Phase 3 — Feature Engineering\n\nIn this phase we perform feature engineering on our cleaned O*NET dataset.\nWe will identify important features, create new meaningful ones, validate them\nusing LightGBM, apply KMeans clustering and finalize our feature set for modelling.\n\n## 0. Setup — Imports & Load Data","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"import pandas as pd\nimport numpy as np\nimport matplotlib.pyplot as plt\nimport seaborn as sns\nimport warnings\nimport shap\n\nwarnings.filterwarnings('ignore')\n\nfrom sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier\nfrom sklearn.inspection import permutation_importance\nfrom sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder, StandardScaler\nfrom sklearn.cluster import KMeans\nfrom sklearn.feature_selection import mutual_info_classif\nimport lightgbm as lgb\n\nsns.set_theme(style=\"whitegrid\", palette=\"muted\")\nplt.rcParams[\"figure.figsize\"] = (12, 5)\n\nprint(\"Core imports done!\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T17:31:41.169236Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T17:31:41.169858Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T17:31:41.178727Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T17:31:41.169824Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T17:31:41.177529Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"df = pd.read_csv('/kaggle/input/notebooks/hamzakamran001/ai-career-path-recommendation-phase-2/onet_clean.csv')\nprint(\"Shape:\", df.shape)\ndf.head()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T17:34:07.814622Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T17:34:07.815469Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T17:34:07.892759Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T17:34:07.815436Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T17:34:07.891742Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 1. Prepare Target Variable\n\nBefore running feature importance algorithms we need to encode our target \ncolumn (Category) into numeric form since all sklearn and LightGBM algorithms \nrequire numeric labels.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Define feature columns and target\nfeature_cols = [c for c in df.columns if any(x in c for x in ['RIASEC_', 'WS_', 'WV_'])]\n\n# Encode target\nle = LabelEncoder()\ndf['Category_Encoded'] = le.fit_transform(df['Category'])\n\nX = df[feature_cols]\ny = df['Category_Encoded']\n\nprint(\"Features:\", len(feature_cols))\nprint(\"Target classes:\", len(le.classes_))\nprint(\"Classes:\", list(le.classes_))\nprint(\"\\nX shape:\", X.shape)\nprint(\"y shape:\", y.shape)","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T17:36:01.803796Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T17:36:01.804918Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T17:36:01.819387Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T17:36:01.804871Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T17:36:01.818358Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"We have 28 features and 22 career categories as our target. The Category \ncolumn is label encoded into numeric form for use with all importance \nalgorithms. The original Category column is kept for reference.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 2. Feature Importance — 5 Algorithms\n\n### 2.1 Random Forest Importance","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"rf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)\nrf.fit(X, y)\n\nrf_importance = pd.DataFrame({\n    'Feature': feature_cols,\n    'Importance': rf.feature_importances_\n}).sort_values('Importance', ascending=False)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\nsns.barplot(data=rf_importance, x='Importance', y='Feature', palette='viridis')\nplt.title(\"Random Forest — Feature Importance\")\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()\n\nprint(rf_importance.to_string())","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T17:37:26.780722Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T17:37:26.781754Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T17:37:28.291323Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T17:37:26.781705Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T17:37:28.290035Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Random Forest measures feature importance by calculating how much each feature \nreduces impurity across all decision trees. Higher score means the feature is \nmore useful in splitting career categories. The top features here will likely \nbe the dominant RIASEC dimensions since they are the primary career discriminators.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 2.2 LightGBM Importance","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"lgbm = lgb.LGBMClassifier(random_state=42, verbose=-1)\nlgbm.fit(X, y)\n\nlgbm_importance = pd.DataFrame({\n    'Feature': feature_cols,\n    'Importance': lgbm.feature_importances_\n}).sort_values('Importance', ascending=False)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\nsns.barplot(data=lgbm_importance, x='Importance', y='Feature', palette='magma')\nplt.title(\"LightGBM — Feature Importance\")\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()\n\nprint(lgbm_importance.to_string())","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T17:38:01.778160Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T17:38:01.779455Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T17:38:04.545928Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T17:38:01.779420Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T17:38:04.544993Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"LightGBM measures importance by counting how many times each feature is used \nto split data across all boosting trees. Compared to Random Forest, LightGBM \nis faster and often highlights different features as important since it builds \ntrees sequentially rather than independently.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 2.3 Mutual Information","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"mi_scores = mutual_info_classif(X, y, random_state=42)\n\nmi_importance = pd.DataFrame({\n    'Feature': feature_cols,\n    'Importance': mi_scores\n}).sort_values('Importance', ascending=False)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\nsns.barplot(data=mi_importance, x='Importance', y='Feature', palette='coolwarm')\nplt.title(\"Mutual Information — Feature Importance\")\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()\n\nprint(mi_importance.to_string())","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T17:39:31.458822Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T17:39:31.460023Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T17:39:32.623685Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T17:39:31.459992Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T17:39:32.622731Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Mutual Information measures how much knowing a feature reduces uncertainty \nabout the target career category. Unlike tree based methods it captures \nnon-linear relationships between features and the target. A score of 0 \nmeans the feature is completely independent of the target.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 2.4 Permutation Importance","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"perm = permutation_importance(rf, X, y, n_repeats=10, random_state=42)\n\nperm_importance = pd.DataFrame({\n    'Feature': feature_cols,\n    'Importance': perm.importances_mean\n}).sort_values('Importance', ascending=False)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\nsns.barplot(data=perm_importance, x='Importance', y='Feature', palette='Blues_r')\nplt.title(\"Permutation Importance — Feature Importance\")\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()\n\nprint(perm_importance.to_string())","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T17:40:20.758586Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T17:40:20.758948Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T17:40:28.256493Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T17:40:20.758923Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T17:40:28.255422Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Permutation Importance measures how much model performance drops when a \nfeature's values are randomly shuffled. If shuffling a feature causes a \nbig drop in accuracy it means that feature was genuinely important. This \nis more reliable than tree based importance since it directly measures \nimpact on model performance rather than split counts.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### 2.5 SHAP Values","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(rf)\nshap_values = explainer.shap_values(X)\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\nshap.summary_plot(shap_values, X, plot_type=\"bar\", show=False)\nplt.title(\"SHAP — Mean Feature Importance Across All Classes\")\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T17:40:59.005810Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T17:40:59.006396Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T17:41:16.681325Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T17:40:59.006362Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T17:41:16.680334Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) assigns each feature an importance score \nbased on game theory. It measures the contribution of each feature to every \nindividual prediction. Unlike other methods SHAP is both globally and locally \ninterpretable — it tells us not just which features matter overall but how \nmuch each feature pushed a specific prediction in a particular direction. \nIt is considered the most reliable and explainable feature importance method.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 3. Create New Meaningful Features\n\nBased on the feature importance results above we now engineer new features \nthat capture relationships between existing dimensions. These new features \naim to improve the model's ability to differentiate between career categories.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Hardcode originals — never use filter after new cols exist\nriasec_cols_orig = ['RIASEC_Artistic', 'RIASEC_Conventional', 'RIASEC_Enterprising',\n                    'RIASEC_Investigative', 'RIASEC_Realistic', 'RIASEC_Social']\n\n# Drop if already exist from previous runs\nfor col in ['RIASEC_Spread', 'IC_Index', 'Leadership_Social_Score']:\n    if col in df.columns:\n        df.drop(columns=[col], inplace=True)\n\n# Now create cleanly\ndf['RIASEC_Spread'] = df[riasec_cols_orig].max(axis=1) - df[riasec_cols_orig].min(axis=1)\ndf['IC_Index'] = df['RIASEC_Investigative'] + df['RIASEC_Conventional']\ndf['Leadership_Social_Score'] = (df['WS_Leadership'] +\n                                  df['RIASEC_Social'] +\n                                  df['RIASEC_Enterprising'])\n\nnew_features = ['RIASEC_Spread', 'IC_Index', 'Leadership_Social_Score']\n\nprint(\"New features created cleanly!\")\nprint(df[new_features].describe().round(3))","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T18:09:31.139092Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T18:09:31.139818Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T18:09:31.170750Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T18:09:31.139788Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T18:09:31.169413Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"We engineered 8 new features, each targeting a specific weakness in the \nraw feature set:\n\n- **RIASEC_Spread** — difference between max and min RIASEC score. A high \nspread means very focused interests pointing clearly toward one career cluster. \nA low spread means broad interests with no strong direction.\n\n- **IC_Index** — sum of Investigative and Conventional scores. Confirmed by \nall 5 importance algorithms as the two strongest predictors of tech careers \n(Computer/IT, Engineering, Science). This composite amplifies that signal.\n\n- **Leadership_Social_Score** — Leadership work style combined with Social \nand Enterprising RIASEC scores. A strong composite predictor for Management, \nBusiness/Finance and Sales career categories.\n\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 4. LightGBM Performance to measure the Before vs After New Features","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score\n\nX_before = df[feature_cols]\nscores_before = cross_val_score(\n    lgb.LGBMClassifier(random_state=42, verbose=-1),\n    X_before, y, cv=5, scoring='accuracy'\n)\n\nX_after = df[feature_cols + new_features]\nscores_after = cross_val_score(\n    lgb.LGBMClassifier(random_state=42, verbose=-1),\n    X_after, y, cv=5, scoring='accuracy'\n)\n\nprint(\"=== LightGBM Performance Comparison ===\")\nprint(f\"\\nBefore new features: {scores_before.mean():.4f} (+/- {scores_before.std():.4f})\")\nprint(f\"After new features:  {scores_after.mean():.4f} (+/- {scores_after.std():.4f})\")\nprint(f\"\\nImprovement: {(scores_after.mean() - scores_before.mean())*100:.2f}%\")\n\nplt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))\nplt.bar(['Before\\n(28 features)', 'After\\n(31 features)'],\n        [scores_before.mean(), scores_after.mean()],\n        color=['#534AB7', '#1D9E75'], width=0.4)\nplt.ylabel(\"Cross Validation Accuracy\")\nplt.title(\"LightGBM Accuracy — Before vs After Feature Engineering\")\nplt.ylim(0.5, 1.0)\nfor i, v in enumerate([scores_before.mean(), scores_after.mean()]):\n    plt.text(i, v + 0.01, f'{v:.4f}', ha='center', fontweight='bold')\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T18:09:48.514824Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T18:09:48.515198Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T18:10:07.197407Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T18:09:48.515166Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T18:10:07.196610Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"We use 5-fold cross validation to fairly compare model performance before \nand after adding the engineered features. Cross validation splits the data \ninto 5 parts, trains on 4 and tests on 1 each time, giving a more reliable \naccuracy estimate than a single train-test split. An improvement in accuracy \nafter adding new features confirms that our engineered features carry genuine \npredictive signal.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 5. Drop Weak Original Features\n\nBased on the feature importance plot we identify a clear gap in importance \nscores. Features above the gap contribute meaningful signal while features \nbelow the gap add noise. We use this natural cutoff to decide which features \nto drop.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Check importance of original features using LightGBM\nlgbm2 = lgb.LGBMClassifier(random_state=42, verbose=-1)\nlgbm2.fit(df[feature_cols + new_features], y)\n\nimportance_df = pd.DataFrame({\n    'Feature': feature_cols + new_features,\n    'Importance': lgbm2.feature_importances_\n}).sort_values('Importance', ascending=False)\n\nprint(importance_df.to_string())\nprint(f\"\\nFeatures with zero importance: {importance_df[importance_df['Importance']==0]['Feature'].tolist()}\")\n\n# Plot\nplt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))\nsns.barplot(data=importance_df, x='Importance', y='Feature', palette='viridis')\nplt.title(\"Feature Importance — Full Feature Set (Original + Engineered)\")\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T18:12:32.410584Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T18:12:32.411212Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T18:12:35.297922Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T18:12:32.411179Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T18:12:35.296526Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"We check importance of all features including the 3 new ones to identify \nwhich original features have zero or near-zero importance. Features with \nzero importance contribute nothing to the model and can be safely dropped \nto reduce noise and improve generalization.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### We are checking the weakest features by importance in the tail","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"print(importance_df.tail(10).to_string())","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T18:16:46.568088Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T18:16:46.568687Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T18:16:46.577323Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T18:16:46.568634Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T18:16:46.575963Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"A clear importance gap was found between `WS_Adaptability/Flexibility` (946) \nand the bottom 4 Work Values which all score below 820. This gap indicates \nthese 4 Work Value features contribute significantly less signal than all \nother features. \n# Feature Dropping Decision: \n### \"Because after dropping the 4 features I was having tha drop in my accuracy by -1.94% ... so it was a clear message that I should reatin all original features because all features are contributing to the accuracy\" ","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 6. Standardization of New Engineered Features\n\nOur original 28 features were already scaled to 0 to 1 in Phase 2 using \nMinMaxScaler. However our 3 newly engineered features were created by \ncombining those scaled features and may have different ranges. We need \nto scale them to match the same 0 to 1 range.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler\n\n# Check ranges of new features before scaling\nprint(\"=== Ranges BEFORE scaling ===\")\nprint(df[new_features].describe().loc[['min', 'max']].round(4))\n\n# Scale only the 3 new engineered features\nscaler = MinMaxScaler()\ndf[new_features] = scaler.fit_transform(df[new_features])\n\n# Verify\nprint(\"\\n=== Ranges AFTER scaling ===\")\nprint(df[new_features].describe().loc[['min', 'max']].round(4))\n\nprint(\"\\nAll features now on same 0 to 1 scale!\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T18:25:23.486641Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T18:25:23.487616Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T18:25:23.526325Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T18:25:23.487578Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T18:25:23.525205Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"The 3 engineered features were on different ranges since they are sums and \ndifferences of the original scaled features. For example IC_Index was the \nsum of two 0 to 1 features giving a range of 0 to 2. MinMaxScaler brings \nall 3 new features to the same 0 to 1 range as the original features \nensuring no single feature dominates distance calculations in our \nrecommendation model.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 7. KMeans Clustering — New Feature Creation\n\nAs required in Phase 3 we explore whether KMeans clustering can generate \na meaningful new feature. We cluster occupations based on their RIASEC \nprofiles and add the cluster label as a new categorical feature.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_score\n\nriasec_cols_orig = ['RIASEC_Artistic', 'RIASEC_Conventional', 'RIASEC_Enterprising',\n                    'RIASEC_Investigative', 'RIASEC_Realistic', 'RIASEC_Social']\n\n# Find optimal K using silhouette score\nsilhouette_scores = []\nK_range = range(2, 10)\n\nfor k in K_range:\n    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)\n    labels = kmeans.fit_predict(df[riasec_cols_orig])\n    score = silhouette_score(df[riasec_cols_orig], labels)\n    silhouette_scores.append(score)\n    print(f\"K={k}: silhouette score = {score:.4f}\")\n\n# Plot\nplt.figure(figsize=(10, 4))\nplt.plot(K_range, silhouette_scores, marker='o', color='#534AB7', linewidth=2)\nplt.title(\"KMeans Silhouette Scores — Finding Optimal K\")\nplt.xlabel(\"Number of Clusters (K)\")\nplt.ylabel(\"Silhouette Score\")\nplt.xticks(K_range)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()\n\nbest_k = K_range[silhouette_scores.index(max(silhouette_scores))]\nprint(f\"\\nBest K: {best_k}\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T18:26:19.945968Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T18:26:19.947169Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T18:26:20.957224Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T18:26:19.947130Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T18:26:20.956086Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### Apply KMeans with Optimal K=5","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"final_feature_cols = feature_cols + new_features\n\n# Test if cluster feature improves model\nfinal_with_cluster = final_feature_cols + ['RIASEC_Cluster']\nscores_cluster = cross_val_score(\n    lgb.LGBMClassifier(random_state=42, verbose=-1),\n    df[final_with_cluster], y, cv=5, scoring='accuracy'\n)\n\nprint(f\"Baseline:                {scores_before.mean():.4f}\")\nprint(f\"With new features:       {scores_after.mean():.4f}\")\nprint(f\"With cluster added:      {scores_cluster.mean():.4f}\")\nprint(f\"Improvement vs baseline: {(scores_cluster.mean()-scores_before.mean())*100:+.2f}%\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T18:27:45.639172Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T18:27:45.639534Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T18:27:57.348724Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T18:27:45.639505Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T18:27:57.347585Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# Final confirmed feature set\nfinal_feature_cols = feature_cols + new_features + ['RIASEC_Cluster']\n\nprint(\"=== Final Feature Set ===\")\nprint(f\"Original features:     {len(feature_cols)}\")\nprint(f\"Engineered features:   {len(new_features)}\")\nprint(f\"KMeans cluster:        1\")\nprint(f\"Total:                 {len(final_feature_cols)}\")\nprint(f\"\\nFinal accuracy:        {scores_cluster.mean():.4f}\")\nprint(f\"Improvement:           {(scores_cluster.mean()-scores_before.mean())*100:+.2f}%\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T18:29:12.466113Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T18:29:12.467409Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T18:29:12.475466Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T18:29:12.467361Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T18:29:12.474116Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"### KMeans Clustering — Decision","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"The RIASEC_Cluster feature produced 5 meaningful career personality groups \nthat align well with real career domains. Although it did not improve \naccuracy further it also did not hurt performance. We keep it as it adds \ninterpretability to our recommendation system and satisfies the requirement \nof exploring KMeans as a feature creation method.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## 8. Save Final Dataset","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"df_final = df[['SOC_Code', 'Title', 'Category', 'Dominant_RIASEC'] + final_feature_cols]\n\ndf_final.to_csv('onet_phase3.csv', index=False)\n\nprint(\"Saved: onet_phase3.csv\")\nprint(f\"Shape: {df_final.shape}\")\nprint(f\"\\nFeature breakdown:\")\nprint(f\"  Original features:   {len(feature_cols)}\")\nprint(f\"  Engineered features: {len(new_features)}\")\nprint(f\"  KMeans cluster:      1\")\nprint(f\"  Total ML features:   {len(final_feature_cols)}\")\nprint(f\"\\nFinal model accuracy: {scores_cluster.mean():.4f}\")\nprint(f\"Improvement over baseline: {(scores_cluster.mean()-scores_before.mean())*100:+.2f}%\")","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2026-03-20T18:30:45.020735Z","iopub.execute_input":"2026-03-20T18:30:45.022304Z","iopub.status.idle":"2026-03-20T18:30:45.090352Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2026-03-20T18:30:45.022258Z","shell.execute_reply":"2026-03-20T18:30:45.089255Z"}},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## Phase 3 Summary\n\n| Step | Action | Result |\n|------|--------|--------|\n| 1 | Feature importance — 5 algorithms | Identified RIASEC as dominant group |\n| 2 | Created 8 candidate features | Tested individually |\n| 3 | Kept best 3 engineered features | Accuracy improved +0.91% |\n| 4 | Tested dropping weak features | Dropped features hurt model — kept all |\n| 5 | Scaled new features to 0 to 1 | All features on consistent scale |\n| 6 | KMeans clustering K=5 | Added RIASEC_Cluster feature |\n| 7 | Final accuracy | 0.5943 vs baseline 0.5851 |\n\n**Final dataset: 873 rows x 32 columns — ready for Phase 4 modelling.**","metadata":{}}]}